Analysis of Undergraduate Courses at Buffalo State College (2015-2023)

Introduction

This report presents a comprehensive analysis of undergraduate courses offered at Buffalo State College from 2015 to 2023, excluding summer sessions. The primary objective is to provide a detailed overview of course offerings across various departments and academic terms. Utilizing Python libraries such as Pandas, Requests, and BeautifulSoup, we extracted data from the college’s course listings on their registrar’s website. The process involved web scraping to gather data, processing it to count courses by their unique CRN (Course Reference Number), and organizing the information into a user-friendly format.

 Methodology

·      The methodology for this analysis involved several key steps:

Web Scraping: Utilized the requests library to fetch HTML content from the Buffalo State College registrar’s website and BeautifulSoup to parse and extract course information, including the year, semester, department, and CRN.

·      URL Construction: Developed a construct URL function to generate URLs dynamically for each academic year and semester, facilitating the scraping of data across multiple years and semesters.

·      Data Aggregation and Grouping: Employed Pandas to aggregate the scraped data into a DataFrame and used the groupby method to organize the data by year, semester, department, and the count of courses.

·      DataFrame Transformation: Transformed the DataFrame to display each year as a column, with nested details for each semester, department, and the total number of courses offered.

·      Renaming Columns: Improved the DataFrame’s readability and clarity by renaming its columns.

·      Exporting to Excel: Exported the final DataFrame to an Excel file for ease of analysis and

sharing.

Conclusion

This project effectively demonstrates the practical application of Python’s data handling and web scraping capabilities in solving real-world problems in the academic sector. The automation of course data collection from a dynamic website and the use of robust data manipulation techniques allowed us to create a single, comprehensive DataFrame of several years’ worth of course information. This streamlined the task of academic planning and analysis and underscored the versatility and efficiency of Python and its libraries. The resulting detailed Excel file is a valuable tool for academic and administrative planning, providing a structured representation of the college’s course offerings over an eight-year period and demonstrating Python’s ability to bridge the gap between raw data extraction and meaningful analysis.
